Streaming Service and Data Analysis¶

5 May 2021

Introduction¶

Netflix is a streaming service that offers a wide variety of award-winning TV shows, movies, anime, documentaries, and more on thousands of internet-connected devices.

In this project, I will programme a model of Netflix in Python. I create the class User to represent subscribers of the streaming service and the class FavouritePlaylist, which is a playlist of the user's favourite shows (Task 1). I will also implement a searching algorithm for shows to create a search engine for users (Task 2).

Finally, I will conduct some data analysis on Netflix shows (Task 3). Netflix has more than 4,000 movies and more than 1,900 TV shows from a wide variety of genres. Given such a wide range of shows, I wish to analyse trends in the shows on Netflix.

Specifically, I will use the data to:
1) Analyse popular topics in shows

  • Find the most popular topics for all shows of all time
  • Find how popular topics have changed over the years (trends)

2) Analyse cast and directors of shows

  • Find the pairs of actors or actresses that often work together
  • Find the pairs of actors/actresses and directors that often work together

3) Find shows that are most related to one another. This is useful for creating a recommendation system for users in our streaming service.

Data Description¶

In this project, I use the following data:

netflix_data: A csv file of data of all shows on Netflix, from kaggle. For each show, there is information on its

  • type: Identifier - A Movie or TV Show
  • title: Title of the Movie / Tv Show
  • director: Director of the Movie
  • cast: Actors involved in the movie / show
  • country: Country where the movie / show was produced
  • date_added: Date it was added on Netflix
  • release_year: Actual Release year of the move / show
  • rating: TV Rating of the movie / show
  • duration: Total Duration - in minutes or number of seasons
  • listed_in: Genre
  • description: The summary description

stopping_words: A txt file of stopping words to remove when analysing show descriptions, so that we are left with the keywords only

Task 2: Search Method¶

For this task, I re-implemented the searching method in the streaming service to have a smarter searching engine.

Code location:

  • streaming_service.py in the src folder

This code uses code from the following modules:

  • index.py in the src folder
  • natural_language_processing.py in the src folder
  • merge_dicts.py in the src folder

a. Rationale behind the program design

Index

  1. I chose to include the shows title, cast and descriptions in the search index as these three features are the most important features that people search for.

  2. I chose to use dict as the container for my index. With a dictionary, given a key, we can immediately and directly obtain the value for that key without having to look through all the other shows. Hence, dict significantly reduces the time needed to search for shows in the index. In contrast, if we used a list, we would have to loop through the entire list until we find the show we need, which can be extremely time-consuming for large data sets.

  3. Apart from the function create_index, I also created an additional function in index.py, which is add_to_index. create_index can be used when one wants to create an index from scratch. add_to_index can be used when one wants to add to an existing index, which is useful for updating the show index when new shows are added.

Streaming Service

  1. I chose to create the index at the start and save it as a class variable, so that it does not need to be created every time a user wants to search for something (which would be very time consuming).

  2. I modified the add_show and remove_show methods such that the index will be updated when new shows are added or removed. For add_show, I used the function add_to_index to add the new show to the index.

  3. Hence, when initialising the StreamingService, I did not choose to use the method create_index to create the class variable self._index. Instead, I left the index as a blank dictionary. This is because we call on the method add_show when initialising the class variable self._shows and add_show automatically adds the new show to the streaming service index.

b. Creating an instance netflix from StreamingService and doing some searches with it to show how the search method works.

In [67]:
import pandas as pd
from streaming_service import StreamingService

netflix_titles = pd.read_csv('../data/netflix_titles.csv')
columns_to_drop = ['director', 'release_year', 'country', 'listed_in']
for column in columns_to_drop:
    netflix_titles.drop(column, inplace = True, axis = 1)

netflix_titles.rename(columns = {'date_added' : 'year_added'}, inplace = True)
netflix_titles['year_added'] = netflix_titles['year_added'].fillna('') # Remove NaN values which would interrupt the for loop in the next line
for index in netflix_titles.index:
        netflix_titles['year_added'][index] = netflix_titles['year_added'][index][-4:]

netflix = StreamingService('netflix', netflix_titles)

c. Limitations

  1. The search method cannot search for titles in foreign languages very well. For example, if we search "", it will be successful.
In [87]:
netflix.search_show('')
Out[87]:
[ (TV Show)]

But if we search for part of the word, such as "", no results will appear.

In [88]:
netflix.search_show('')

Sorry, no shows were found for the keywords "". Try other keywords.
  1. The search engine also cannot present the right results if there are typos. For example,
In [103]:
netflix.search_show('dr suss') # Instead of "dr seuss"

Sorry, no shows were found for the keywords "dr suss". Try other keywords.

1. Analysis on Description Column¶

Given the huge number of shows on Netflix, it would be useful to find out trends in the types of shows that Netflix offers. We will use the word counts on Netflix show descriptions to analyse the following two things:

  1. The most popular topics for all shows of all time (by finding the most common keywords in all show descriptions)
  2. How popular topics have changed over the years (by finding the most common keywords in show descriptions for each year and plotting a graph to see the trends over time)

Part 1. Finding the most popular topics for all shows of all time¶

Before analysing, we clean up the descriptions by making all words lowercase, removing punctuation and stemming the words. We also remove all stopping words to get the keywords from each description only. We use the processed function from the module natural_language_processing to do this and then save all the keywords as a list. Afterwards, we split the list up such that each keyword has its own cell in the DataFrame.

In [116]:
from natural_language_processing import processed
In [117]:
keywords_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['Show Name', 'Year', 'List of Keywords']) # Create new dataframe to store keywords
for index, show in netflix_titles.iterrows():
    keywords_new = processed(show['description'].split()) # Transforms description into individual keywords. Stem words, removes punctuation and stopping words, then Transforms description into individual keywords. 
    keywords_df.loc[index] = [show['title'], show['release_year'], keywords_new]

keywords_temp_df = keywords_df['List of Keywords'].apply(pd.Series) # Temporary keywords dataframe to split each keyword into its own cell
keywords_temp_df = keywords_temp_df.rename(columns = lambda x : 'keyword_' + str(x)) # Rename column name to keyword_(number)
keywords_df = pd.concat([keywords_df[:], keywords_temp_df[:]], axis = 1) # Join keywords_temp_df and keywords_df
keywords_df.head(10)

Now, we find the most common keywords among all the shows' descriptions and find the number of times each keyword appear. This gives us an idea of what topics are generally the most popular among Netflix shows, assuming that number of movies produced about a specific topic is positively corelated with that topic's popularity. Note that there may be some spelling errors as some words have been stemmed incorrectly by the stemmer.

In [118]:
keyword_counts = keywords_df.loc[:, "keyword_0":"keyword_26"].apply(pd.Series.value_counts) # Counts each unique occurrence of a keyword in the dataframe.
keyword_counts['count'] = keyword_counts.sum(axis = 1) 
keyword_counts = keyword_counts.loc[:, ['count']] # Only keep the 'count' column
keyword_counts = keyword_counts.sort_values(by = ['count'], ascending = False) # Sort by word frequency, for most frequent to least frequent
keyword_counts = keyword_counts.drop("", axis = 0) # Remove the punctuation "-" from the dataframe that was not removed by earlier processing (it was not stripped with the other punctuation symbols as it was not attached to any word)
keyword_counts = keyword_counts.drop("", axis = 0) # Note that this is a different dash from the one above (this is the long dash)
keyword_counts.head(10)

Hence, we can reasonably assume that "life", "family", "friend", "love" and "world" are among the top topics for Netflix shows. Note that "family" has been incorrectly stemmed to "famili".

Part 2. Finding out how popular topics have changed over the years¶

From the bar graph, we see that most shows on Netflix were released quite recently (ie. in the last decade) and older shows (especially those before 2000) are rare. If we include data from older years when finding the most popular topic in each year, the results are likely to be biased, as the sample size for older years is very small (near 0 for some years).

As a rough gauge, we shall only sample shows from years 2000 to 2020, which is when the majority of the shows on Netflix were released. We do not include 2021 as the year is not over yet, so the data for 2021 is incomplete.

Now, we create function to help us find the most common keywords in each year from 2000 to 2020.

In [122]:
def generate_year_keyword_counts(df, year):
    '''
    This function counts the number of times each keyword appears for show descriptions in a given year from a given dataframe.
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    df : Pandas DataFrame 
        Contains show name, year, list of keywords and each keyword in its own cell in the row
    year : int
        Year to find the most common keywords for

    Returns
    -------
    keyword_year_counts : Pandas DataFrame
        Dataframe of all unique keywords in the year and the number of time each keyword appears in that year
        
    '''
    df2 = df.loc[df['Year'] == year] # Create a new dataframe so as not to modify the original and only keep shows which are released in the given year
    df2 = df2.drop(columns = ['Show Name', 'Year', 'List of Keywords']) # Remove columns that are not needed
    keyword_year_counts = df2.apply(pd.Series.value_counts) 
    keyword_year_counts[str(year)] = keyword_year_counts.sum(axis = 1) # Sum up number of times the keyword appears in a new column, column title is the year
    keyword_year_counts = keyword_year_counts.loc[:,[str(year)]] # Only keep the column with the sum
    if "" in keyword_year_counts.index: 
        keyword_year_counts = keyword_year_counts.drop("",axis = 0) # Remove "" that was not removed during processing
    if ""  in keyword_year_counts.index:
        keyword_year_counts = keyword_year_counts.drop("",axis = 0) # Note that this is a different dash from the one above (this is the long dash)
    return keyword_year_counts

Some observations on popular topics:¶

From this plot, we can see that "family" and life were very popular topics in the early 2000s, reaching the peak of their popularity at around 2003. However, both topics experienced a sharp fall in popularity over the years. There were close to 0 shows on "family" in 2020. From approximately 2016, there were close to 0 shows on "life".
There were also many shows on "friend" in the early 2000s, but the popularity of this topic fell later on. However, it rose in popularity again in 2017, becoming the top keyword for shows in around 2017.
"Love" was an extremely popular topic in the early 2000s. Its popularity fell in around 2003 and fluctuated afterwards, before rising to popularity again. From around 2015 onwards, "love" always remained within the top 4 keywords, showing its popularity today.

Limitations and Areas of Improvement for 3b1¶

  • The stemmer used (nltk's SnowballStemmer) stems some words wrongly. For example, it stems "family" into "famili". To improve the accuracy of language processing, we can either find an alternative stemmer or do some lemmatisation (which considers the context and converts the word to its meaningful base form, reducing the chances of errors).
  • The graph plotted to observe trends in topics is based on the absolute number of shows that have that keyword that year. However, a different number of shows is released every year, which can be due to reasons unrelated unrelated to the popularity of the topic eg. Covid-19 may cause the number of shows produced in 2020 to drop due to filming restrictions during a pandemic. Hence, looking at the absolute number of shows that have that keyword every year may not tell us much about trends in popular topics.
    • Rather, it may be better to plot the changes in ranking of each of the top 7 keywords from 2000-2020, so that we can see their year-on-year popularity in relation to other topics.
  • The line graph is very long. Using rankings would solve the issue of a very long graph as the range of rankings is likely much smaller.

2. Part 1: Finding the pairs of actors or actresses that often work together¶

First, we create a function to help me find all the actor pairs in a given list of actors. Then, we find all the actor pairs for all shows in netflix_titles and find the number of shows each pair has worked on together. This data will be sorted in a dictionary.

In [128]:
# Note: This was adapted from PS4's solution

def get_actor_pairs(actors):
    '''
    Get all pairs from the list "actors"
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    actors : list
        List of cast (actors and actresses) in one show

    Returns
    -------
    actor_pairs : list of tuples
        List of actor/actress pairs, with each tuple being a pair
    '''
    actor_pairs = []
    for actor_1 in actors:
        for actor_2 in actors:
            if actor_1 > actor_2:  # To prevent duplicate pairs 
                actor_pairs.append((actor_1, actor_2))
    return actor_pairs

cast_list = netflix_titles['cast'].to_list() # List of all casts in all shows in netflix_titles
actor_pairs = {} # A dictionary of all actor pairs and the number of shows each pair has worked on together
for cast in cast_list:
    cast = str(cast).split(',')
    for actor_pair in get_actor_pairs(cast):
        if len(actor_pair):
            if actor_pair not in actor_pairs:
                actor_pairs[actor_pair] = 0
            actor_pairs[actor_pair] += 1

Finally, we will find the actor pairs that work together the most often and the number of shows they worked together on.

3. Additional Analysis: Recommendation System¶

By analysing the data, can we identify which shows are most closely related to each other? Using a simple model of counting the number of related features (i.e. actors, keywords etc.), we will match shows to find those that are most related. This is so that after the user watches one show, the streaming service can automatically recommend similar shows for the user to watch next.

In [135]:
features_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = ['List of features'], index = list(netflix_titles['title'])) # Create new dataframe to store features
working_df = netflix_titles # Create a working dataframe so that we do not edit the original netflix_titles
working_df = working_df.fillna('') # Remove entries with empty values (ie. NaN)

for index, show in working_df.iterrows():
    keywords_new = processed(show['description'].split()) # Transforms description into individual keywords. Stems words, removes punctuation and stopping words.
    cast_new = show['cast'].split(',')
    genre_new = show['listed_in'].split(',')
    features_list = keywords_new + cast_new + genre_new + [working_df.at[index,'director'], working_df.at[index,'rating'], working_df.at[index,'country']] # Get all the features and put it into a list
    features_df.at[show['title'], 'List of features'] = features_list

Now, we will create a scoring system based on "relatedness". For each feature two shows have in common, one point will be added to their score. The recommendation system will recommend shows from highest scores (most related) to lowest scores (least realated).

In [136]:
score_df = pd.DataFrame(columns = list(netflix_titles['title']), index = list(netflix_titles['title'])) # Dataframe of all show titles against all show titles to keep track of scores
score_df = score_df.fillna(-1) # By default, fill all scores with '-1', which signifies that two shows are not related at all

def find_related_show(title):
    '''
    Given a show from netflix_titles, ranks all other shows in netflix_titles from most related to least related 
    
    Parameters
    ----------
    title : str
        Title of show that you want to find similar shows to
        
    Raises
    -------
    KeyError 
        If show title cannot be found
    TypeError
        If title given is not of type str

    Returns
    -------
    most_related_shows : DataFrame
        DataFrame
    '''
    try:
        for index, show in features_df.iterrows():
            if score_df.at[title, index] == -1:
                score = len(set(features_df.at[title,'List of features']) & set(features_df.at[index,'List of features'])) # Find the number of common features between two shows to find their relatedness score.
                score_df.at[title, index] = score
                score_df.at[index, title] = score
        most_related_shows = score_df[title].sort_values(ascending = False)
        return most_related_shows[1:] # Do not include index 0 as index 0 (the most similar result) is always the given show itself
    except KeyError:
        raise KeyError('Sorry, show title cannot be found. Please try again.')
    except TypeError:
        raise TypeError(f'Expected a str but {type(title)} was given. Please try again.')

Limitations and Areas of Improvement for 3b3¶

  • We assume all the features (eg. actor, rating, country) are of equal importance so we do not weigh the features when calculating the "relatedness" score. In reality, some features may be more important than others. For example, a show having the same actor as the given show would be considered a "better" recommendation, than a show that has the same rating as the given show. This is because fans may want to watch shows that their favourite actors star in. On the other hand, many shows may have the same ratings like "PG-13" or "R" so rating is not as important when looking for recommended shows.
    • To improve, we can create a weighted scoring system, with some features contributing more to the score than others
  • Since we do not take in any user input or check the user's activity or metrics, the recommendations are very general. To improve, we can also check the user's watch history to recommend similar shows (eg. if the users' watch history has a trend of watching shows from a certain actor, the recommendation system can recommend more shows from the same actor).
    • To improve, we can give the user an option to "sort" the recommendations by the feature that the user thinks is important (eg. 'Sort by similar actors first' or 'Sort by similar country first')
  • The recommendation system may recommend you shows that you are not supposed to watch, based on the age rating. For example, it may recommend you a show rated "R" but you are under 17. To go one step further, I could implement the recommendation system for users and check the age of the user (since users are required to enter their birthday when they create a User account). I can then filter the recommendations to only include the age-appropriate ones.
  • For the "country" feature, if there are multiple countries, all the countries for two shows must match exactly to be considered "related" and to add to their "relatedness" score. Eg. If one show has "South Korea, United States", another show must have "South Korea, United States" too to be considered "related" to the first show. It will not work if it the other show has "United States, South Korea" (in the wrong order) or if the other show only has one country in common like "United States" (partial match). This could be problematic as the two shows have at least one country in common, theoretically they should be considered "related".
    • To fix the problem of countries being in the wrong order, we could use the split.(') function on all the entries in the "country" column of the dataframe to split each country into an individual string (eg. 'United States, South Korea' -> 'United States', 'South Korea') and then sort the individual strings alphabetically.
    • To fix the problem of partial matches, we also use split.(') on the "country" column in the dataframe. Since each country is now an individual string, we can then compare how many countries two shows have in common and calculate their relatedness score respectively. An example:
      • Show 1's countries: 'Brazil', 'France', 'Canada'
      • Show 2's countries: 'France', 'Canada', 'Portugal', 'Mexico'
      • Hence, show 2's relatedness score with regards to show 1 for the "country" feature can be 2/3, since 2/3 countries in show 1 are present in show 2. show 1's relatedness score with regards to 2 can be 1/2, since 2/4 countries in show 2 are present in show 1.
      • However, this would making the scoring system much more complicated as Show 1's relatedness score to Show 2 may be different from Show 2's relatedness score to Show 1 (currently, they are the same), hence for simplicity, I did not implement it.

Conclusion and Reflection¶

In this project, I have improved on my previous programming of Streaming Service, by creating the classes User and Favourite Playlist and by creating a search engine. I also conducted some data analysis on Netflix show data.

Overall Limitations

  • The data we are working with, netflix_titles, is not updated as it was downloaded from Kaggle in May 2021. New shows are constantly being added Netflix, so our data analyses (eg. finding the actor pairs that work together the most) using old data may not be accurate today.
  • Some show data is in foreign languages and thus some methods may not work well. For example, searching for shows in foreign languages with keywords may not be successful. We have demonstrated this earlier with Korean.
  • In reality, a User account may need additional features, such as a password to protect hackers from accessing the account.

Areas of Improvement or Areas for Futher Development

  • For further development on this project, I can implement the reccommendation system into the User class and tailor the recommendations to the user's preferences by analysing the user's watch history and favourites playlist. I can also filter out age-inappropriate shows for the user, since the class User requires the user to enter his/her birthday.
  • It may be helpful to bring in other datasets (eg. IMDB ratings of Netflix shows) to improve the recommendation system. For example, the recommendations generated for the user can be sorted by highest rating to lowest rating based on IMDB ratings. This is especially since many recommendations are often tied with the same score, making them hard to differentiate.
  • I would also improve the search method so that it can recognise typos and autocorrect them for the user (eg. "Suss" -> "Seuss"). This is because in real life, many people type very quickly and often make typos. Sometimes, people may also forget how to spell a movie or actor's name.
  • The search engine can also be trained to recognise slang or short-form (eg. "xmas" -> "Christmas").
  • I can also consider presenting my data analysis of word counts in other forms, such as a word cloud to display the most popular topics visually.
